Wash and dry all produce. Mince @cilantro{¼%ounce}. Zest and halve @lemon{1} (for 4 servings, zest 1 lemon and halve both). Mince @jalapeño{1}, removing ribs and seeds for less heat. Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}(peeled and diced). Trim and halve @zucchini{1} lengthwise; cut crosswise into ½-inch-thick half-moons. Mince or grate @garlic{2%cloves}. Drain and rinse @chickpeas{13.4%ounce}; pat dry with paper towels.

In a #small bowl{}, combine cilantro, @olive oil{2%tbsp}, a pinch of garlic, @salt{pinch}, and @pepper{pinch}. Add lemon juice to taste and as much jalapeño as you like. Taste and add more garlic if desired. In a separate small bowl, combine @sour cream{4%tablespoon}, a pinch of salt, and as much lemon zest as you like. Add @water{1%tsp} 1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

Heat a drizzle of olive oil in a #small pot{} over medium-high heat. Add ¼ of the onion; cook, stirring, until just softened, ~{2-3%minutes}. Stir in ¾ cup water, half the @veggie stock concentrate{2}, and a pinch of salt. Bring to a boil, then stir in @couscous{½%cup}. Turn off heat, cover, and let stand until ready to serve.

Heat a large drizzle of olive oil in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Add zucchini and remaining onion. Cook, stirring, until softened and lightly browned, ~{5-7%minutes}. Add @Tunisian spice blend{1%tablespoon}, remaining garlic, and a big pinch of salt. Cook, stirring, until fragrant, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir ⅓ cup water and remaining stock concentrates into pan. Stir in chickpeas and bring to a low simmer. Cook until liquid is slightly reduced, ~{1-2%minutes}. Reduce heat to low; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon} until melted. Season with salt and pepper.

Fluff couscous with a #fork{}; stir in @butter{1%tablespoon}. Season with salt and pepper. Divide between plates and top with tagine. Top with @almonds{½%ounce} and @dried apricots{1%ounce}. Drizzle with lemon cream and chermoula. Drizzle with @?hot sauce{1%teaspoon} if desired. Cut remaining lemon into wedges; serve on the side.

> Toast almonds before adding if you like.

> Chermoula is chock full of cilantro, garlic, olive oil, lemon, and jalapeño, which adds the perfect punch.

> Tagine's great balance of textures and layers of savory-sweet flavors make this a delicious weeknight dish.